Functionazling Rasters From NEON

Jeff Atkins

June 21, 2016

Start by putting up objectives/tasks that students will be working though:

  1. Import a raster A lidar canopy height model (lidar/Teak_lidarCHM.tif)
  2. For the CHM, set values == 0 to NA (not trees)

  3. classify the raster according to some distribution low medium and tall trees. This could be done using a histogram potentially or we could just decide that <2m is generally grasses / understory, <6m small trees,and the rest are tall trees. A function could import the desired thresholds. Visualize histogram/density and plot vertical cutoff lines.

  4. PLOT - layer the classified raster on top of the hillshade, add a legend for each class - legends are super tricky to simplifying this process with a function would be good. see: http://neon-workwithdata.github.io/neon-data-institute-2016/R/classify-by-threshold-R/ for my take on forcing a legend outside of the plot area using par settings. You may have other better forms of magic to make this work well. :)

  5. Export the plot figure to a pdf publishable

  6. Export the classified raster as a geotiff with NaFlagg = -9999 to an outputs folder.

Step One: Import Raster

chm <- raster("../NEONdata/D17-California/TEAK/2013/lidar/Teak_lidarCHM.tif")

Step Two: Set values == 0 to NA (not trees)

#Sets those 0s to NA
chm[ chm <= 0 ] <- NA

#check this raster out, does it look like trees?
plot(chm,
     main="Canopy Height \n LowerTeakettle, California")

Step Three: Raster Classification By Height

#lets do a histogram and get some distribution
hist(chm)

density(chm)

#Want to focus on tree size class
height.class.m <- c(0, 5, 1,
                         5, 20 , 2,
                         20, 100, 3)

reclass.m <- matrix(height.class.m,
                    ncol = 3,
                    byrow = TRUE)


chm.class <- reclassify(chm, reclass.m)

#here is a draft plot by class
plot(chm.class,
     main = "Teakettle Canopy Height By Class")

density(chm, 
        main = "Canopy heights at Teakettle site\n with bin cuttofs in red",
        xlab = "Height (m)")
#this adds lines to the density plot
abline(v = reclass.m[, 2], col = "red")

Step Four: I Am Legend

STEP Five: Export to .pdf!

# plot outside of the plot region

# make room for a legend
par(xpd = FALSE, mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 4.1))

#here, the xpd is saying "stay inside the corral, don't plot outside boundaries"

#bottom, up, left, right

# plot
pdf("outputs/chm.class.pdf", width = 6, height = 6)
plot(chm.class,
     col=c("grey","blue","green"), # hard code colors, small trees (1)=white,
         #medium (2) = blue,  large trees (3) = green
     main="Vegetation Height \nLower Teakettle",
     legend=F)
# allow legend to plot outside of bounds
par(xpd=TRUE)

# legend x and y position
leg.x <- par()$usr[2] + 20
leg.y <- par()$usr[4] + 50 - (abs(par()$usr[3] - par()$usr[4]) / 2)

# create the legend
legend(leg.x, leg.y,
       legend = c("    <5 m", "5-20 m", "  >20 m"),  # make sure the order matches the colors, next
       fill = c("grey", "blue", "green"),
       bty="n") # turn off border)

# legend((par()$usr[2] + 20), 4103300,  # set x,y legend location
#        legend = c("    <5 m", "5-20 m", "  >20 m"),  # make sure the order matches the colors, next
#        fill = c("grey", "blue", "green"),
#        bty="n") # turn off border
dev.off()

Step Six: Export the raster

writeRaster(chm.class,
            filename="../outputs/TEAK/Teak_nsAspect.tif",
            format="GTiff",
            options="COMPRESS=LZW",
            overwrite = TRUE,
            NAflag = -9999)
